1
00:00:00,080 --> 00:00:00,720
CHAPTER ONE

2
00:00:01,760 --> 00:00:02,960
Tug is Taken Away

3
00:00:04,080 --> 00:00:07,040
DAY ONE - SUNDAY 7TH AUGUST

4
00:00:07,040 --> 00:00:13,200
Tug was running. His legs ached, his feet hurt, 
all his body was screaming at him to stop running.  

5
00:00:14,160 --> 00:00:19,840
But he didn't want to stop. He wanted today's 
run to be better and faster than ever before.  

6
00:00:20,960 --> 00:00:25,600
Now he was nearly at the end of his run, and 
his legs were burning, but he still went on  

7
00:00:25,600 --> 00:00:31,920
running. As he came round the last street corner, 
he saw his own front door, a hundred metres away.  

8
00:00:32,880 --> 00:00:39,680
I mustn't stop now! he thought. I promised 
myself I'd do eight kilometres, and I will!

9
00:00:40,800 --> 00:00:44,080
The church bells were ringing, and 
the blood was beating in his ears.  

10
00:00:45,280 --> 00:00:52,560
Suddenly it all seemed easy, and his legs felt 
strong. I can do it! he said happily to himself.

11
00:00:53,600 --> 00:01:00,720
He reached the front door, and looked at 
his watch. 36 minutes 20 seconds. At last!  

12
00:01:01,840 --> 00:01:07,120
Eight kilometres in less than 37 minutes! 
I've been trying to do that for weeks!

13
00:01:08,240 --> 00:01:14,720
He put his key in the door. Now he could have 
a hot bath. His mother would get home later.  

14
00:01:15,760 --> 00:01:18,880
She had promised to cook him a 
special meal - chicken and chips,  

15
00:01:18,880 --> 00:01:22,880
and a chocolate cake. He smiled 
as he pushed open the door.

16
00:01:24,000 --> 00:01:31,280
Strange! The house was dark, too dark. And 
there was something more... But he was too  

17
00:01:31,280 --> 00:01:36,480
tired to think. Suddenly there was an arm 
round his neck and a hand over his face.  

18
00:01:37,600 --> 00:01:39,840
He fell, and everything went black.

19
00:01:40,720 --> 00:01:44,960
DAY TWO - MONDAY 8TH AUGUST
Fifteen hours later and  

20
00:01:44,960 --> 00:01:49,360
two hundred kilometres away in Derbyshire, 
Jinny Slattery came out of the farmhouse.  

21
00:01:50,480 --> 00:01:54,160
In the moonlight she could see the ridge 
of mountains called Ashdale Great Edge.  

22
00:01:55,280 --> 00:02:00,160
It stood, black and frightening, against the 
sky, with the Castle Rock at its southern end.

23
00:02:01,360 --> 00:02:07,600
Jinny walked away from the farmhouse, and took 
the narrow road up the hill. It was two o'clock in  

24
00:02:07,600 --> 00:02:13,920
the morning, and very quiet. When she reached some 
trees, her father stepped out and touched her arm.

25
00:02:14,960 --> 00:02:21,840
'Oh!' she cried in surprise, and felt angry 
with herself. He had told her to be quiet.

26
00:02:22,880 --> 00:02:28,240
'Follow me,' Joe said, and went on up 
the road. He walked quickly and silently,  

27
00:02:28,240 --> 00:02:29,680
his dog just behind him.

28
00:02:30,640 --> 00:02:33,440
I must remember what he told 
me to do, Jinny thought.

29
00:02:34,480 --> 00:02:35,840
I don't want to make a mistake!

30
00:02:37,120 --> 00:02:41,760
Now they were high up on the moors. 
Further along was an old cottage,  

31
00:02:41,760 --> 00:02:46,400
which Mrs Hollins used to rent to 
summer visitors. It was almost hidden  

32
00:02:46,400 --> 00:02:51,680
by trees. On the right was a gate into a 
field, the field which they had chosen.

33
00:02:52,720 --> 00:02:59,920
Jinny felt sick. She knew what would happen next. 
Joe had already filled every hole in the hedges  

34
00:02:59,920 --> 00:03:05,520
round the field, so the gate was the only way 
out. Now he was putting a net over the gate.

35
00:03:06,720 --> 00:03:09,040
Just then they heard a car driving up the road.

36
00:03:10,080 --> 00:03:18,080
'Where is it going?' asked Jinny. 'This road 
only goes to the moors and Mrs Hollins' cottage.'

37
00:03:18,080 --> 00:03:21,440
'Visitors,' said Joe softly, 
'probably renting the cottage.  

38
00:03:22,560 --> 00:03:24,800
Keep quiet, they won't see us in the dark.'

39
00:03:25,920 --> 00:03:29,440
The car drove slowly past them and 
stopped in front of the cottage.  

40
00:03:30,560 --> 00:03:34,640
Jinny could hear the voices of a man 
and a woman, and then a strange noise.  

41
00:03:35,680 --> 00:03:40,320
Were they pulling something heavy into the 
house? She couldn't see what was happening.

42
00:03:41,360 --> 00:03:46,000
When it was quiet again, Joe 
said softly, 'Remember, Jinny.  

43
00:03:46,000 --> 00:03:50,640
Remember everything I told you,' and went 
silently into the field, followed by his dog.

44
00:03:51,760 --> 00:03:58,000
Jinny was shaking now, not from cold but from 
fear and excitement. She knew that Joe and the  

45
00:03:58,000 --> 00:04:03,520
dog were moving slowly through the field. She 
thought of the hare, lying asleep in the grass.  

46
00:04:04,640 --> 00:04:09,440
It would try to escape through the gate. 
Then she must do what Joe had told her.

47
00:04:10,400 --> 00:04:17,920
I can't! she thought. But she had 
to do it. 'If you want to eat meat,  

48
00:04:17,920 --> 00:04:23,280
you must be able to kill an animal,' Joe had 
said. 'Why should other people do it for you?'

49
00:04:24,320 --> 00:04:29,920
But in the end it almost seemed easy. The hare 
tried to jump through the gate and was caught  

50
00:04:29,920 --> 00:04:37,120
in the net. Automatically Jinny hit its neck hard, 
and the hare's warm dead body fell at her feet. As  

51
00:04:37,120 --> 00:04:43,280
she was looking at it, Joe arrived. 'Good girl,' 
he said, and started taking the net off the gate.

52
00:04:44,320 --> 00:04:46,560
Just then a loud noise broke the silence.  

53
00:04:47,680 --> 00:04:50,480
It was the sound of hammering, 
and it came from the cottage.

54
00:04:51,520 --> 00:04:59,200
'What's that?' Jinny cried. But Joe didn't stop 
what he was doing. 'Nothing to do with us,'  

55
00:04:59,200 --> 00:05:02,400
he replied. That was what he always said.  

56
00:05:03,520 --> 00:05:07,200
For him the Slattery family was much 
more important than the outside world.

57
00:05:08,320 --> 00:05:11,840
'But if someone hears,' said Jinny, 
'they'll come up here to see,  

58
00:05:11,840 --> 00:05:15,440
and then the police will catch us... 
stealing hares that don't belong to us!'

59
00:05:16,640 --> 00:05:22,160
'Don't worry,' said Joe calmly. 'From the village 
you can't hear anything that happens up here.  

60
00:05:23,200 --> 00:05:26,240
We'll make sure that we get home 
with the hare before anyone comes.'

61
00:05:27,440 --> 00:05:33,840
They walked down the road to the farmhouse. 
I'm not like Joe, thought Jinny. I always  

62
00:05:33,840 --> 00:05:38,560
want to know why things happen. And I want 
to know what's happening in that cottage!
 
 

63
00:05:39,600 --> 00:05:43,120
10.00 A.M.
Seven hours later,  

64
00:05:43,120 --> 00:05:48,400
Tug woke up in the cottage. The room was 
full of sunshine and very loud music.  

65
00:05:49,600 --> 00:05:54,080
Above him was a high window, with strong 
bars across it, and blue sky outside.

66
00:05:55,200 --> 00:05:58,640
It must be a dream. He wanted to wake up,  

67
00:05:58,640 --> 00:06:03,120
and find himself in his own bedroom. 
But the dream did not go away.

68
00:06:04,320 --> 00:06:10,720
Suddenly he noticed a woman at the door. She 
was about thirty, and very thin, with long legs,  

69
00:06:10,720 --> 00:06:16,080
long brown hair and long fingers. But her eyes 
were the most interesting thing about her.  

70
00:06:17,120 --> 00:06:19,840
They were large and yellow-brown, almost golden.

71
00:06:20,720 --> 00:06:23,680
She said something, but he couldn't 
hear her because of the music.  

72
00:06:24,880 --> 00:06:26,640
'Sorry, I didn't hear that,' he said.

73
00:06:27,680 --> 00:06:31,200
'I said how are you feeling?' she shouted angrily.

74
00:06:32,320 --> 00:06:39,040
Tug tried to sit up. When he moved his 
head, he felt sick. 'What happened?'  

75
00:06:40,160 --> 00:06:46,400
he asked. 'I don't remember this place.' 
He was sure he had never been there before.

76
00:06:47,440 --> 00:06:49,680
The woman sounded careless, unworried.  

77
00:06:50,720 --> 00:06:53,920
'You fell... hit your head ... 
we had to carry you upstairs...'

78
00:06:55,040 --> 00:06:58,400
It was important, but he couldn't 
hear because the music was so loud.  

79
00:06:59,440 --> 00:07:04,080
'It's too noisy! We can't talk!' he shouted.

80
00:07:05,120 --> 00:07:08,720
She didn't answer, but opened the 
bedroom door and shouted to someone.  

81
00:07:09,760 --> 00:07:15,840
The music was louder through the open door. Tug 
couldn't think, and his head was still hurting.

82
00:07:16,400 --> 00:07:22,560
A man came into the room, with slow, unhurried 
steps. He had a strangely white face,  

83
00:07:22,560 --> 00:07:29,840
with cold blue eyes and thick black hair. The 
woman spoke quietly to him. Tug couldn't hear.

84
00:07:30,560 --> 00:07:38,640
'Look,' said Tug. He wanted to sound as polite as 
possible. 'I don't remember anything. Where am I?  

85
00:07:39,760 --> 00:07:45,280
And how did I get here? And who are you? 
Please will you tell me what's happening?'

86
00:07:46,400 --> 00:07:50,320
'Don't worry,' said the man 
coldly. 'You hit your head  

87
00:07:50,320 --> 00:07:56,080
and you've forgotten a few things. 
That's all. You'll be fine after a rest.'

88
00:07:57,200 --> 00:08:01,360
He turned to go, but Tug reached 
out for his arm. 'Please!'  

89
00:08:02,480 --> 00:08:05,760
he cried wildly. 'You must tell me something!

90
00:08:06,880 --> 00:08:10,400
'We're in the cottage that we've rented 
for our holiday, in the north of England.  

91
00:08:11,520 --> 00:08:14,320
You remember? Now try and sleep.'

92
00:08:15,360 --> 00:08:22,000
'But who are you?' shouted Tug. They 
were both leaving the room. The man  

93
00:08:22,000 --> 00:08:26,480
said something that Tug didn't hear, ... 
mirror...' and closed the door behind him.  

94
00:08:27,600 --> 00:08:30,640
Tug jumped out of bed and ran 
to the door, but it was locked.

95
00:08:31,840 --> 00:08:39,120
Suddenly he felt very cold. The music still filled 
his head, but it didn't stop him thinking now. He  

96
00:08:39,120 --> 00:08:44,080
had hoped this was all a mistake, that they would 
answer his questions and explain everything,  

97
00:08:44,080 --> 00:08:49,520
or take him home. But now he realized that they 
wanted to keep him a prisoner in that room.

98
00:08:50,560 --> 00:08:56,320
It was a small room just under the roof, with 
only a bed and a cupboard in it. He looked up at  

99
00:08:56,320 --> 00:09:03,760
the window above his head. They had hammered the 
bars on to it very recently. He couldn't escape  

100
00:09:03,760 --> 00:09:10,880
that way. He sat on the bed and put his head in 
his hands. He had never felt so miserable and  

101
00:09:10,880 --> 00:09:16,960
frightened before. Just then he thought of his 
mother. He knew what she would say to him now.  

102
00:09:18,160 --> 00:09:24,800
Why do you always feel sorry for yourself? Get up 
and do something! He felt better when he thought  

103
00:09:24,800 --> 00:09:31,760
of her small angry face. Cheer up, Tug! he told 
himself, and got up to look in the cupboard.

104
00:09:32,720 --> 00:09:38,880
He was very pleased to find his clothes there, all 
ready for him to wear. But as he reached for them,  

105
00:09:38,880 --> 00:09:43,040
he noticed something. On the inside 
of the door was a long mirror.  

106
00:09:44,080 --> 00:09:50,560
What had the man said? Something about a 
mirror. Slowly Tug turned to look at himself.

107
00:09:51,600 --> 00:09:56,640
And for a second he was in a bad dream. 
Because the face in the mirror was not his.  

108
00:09:57,760 --> 00:10:05,040
Then he realized what was different - his hair. It 
was black, not fair. His face seemed very white,  

109
00:10:05,040 --> 00:10:10,480
and his blue eyes looked coldly back at him. He 
looked at himself in the mirror for a long time.  

110
00:10:11,680 --> 00:10:14,720
With the black hair, white 
face and cold blue eyes,  

111
00:10:14,720 --> 00:10:18,320
he looked just like the man. 
He could almost be his son.
 
 

112
00:10:19,440 --> 00:10:23,440
12.45 P.M.
Jinny ran into the village.  

113
00:10:24,640 --> 00:10:29,280
Her father had asked her to post something, so 
she wanted to get to the post office before it  

114
00:10:29,280 --> 00:10:34,880
closed for lunch. Outside the post office 
she saw Rachel Hollins sitting on a wall.  

115
00:10:36,080 --> 00:10:42,160
Rachel's father was the village policeman, and her 
mother worked in the post office. Rachel was very  

116
00:10:42,160 --> 00:10:50,240
pretty, and always wore beautiful clothes. 'Hello 
Jinny!' she cried. 'Do you like my new dress?'

117
00:10:51,440 --> 00:10:56,640
'Very nice,' replied Jinny crossly. 'But I 
couldn't wear that for working on the farm.'

118
00:10:57,600 --> 00:11:06,160
'Oh, I forgot!' said Rachel. She smiled sweetly - 
too sweetly, and Jinny wanted to hit her. 'I'm so  

119
00:11:06,160 --> 00:11:14,320
sorry! Poor Jinny! You have to work so hard and 
you never have any new clothes and... She stopped  

120
00:11:14,320 --> 00:11:19,840
as she saw someone behind Jinny 'I must go in and 
have lunch,' she said quickly, and ran inside.

121
00:11:20,960 --> 00:11:24,720
Jinny turned to see who was 
behind her. It was a woman,  

122
00:11:24,720 --> 00:11:30,480
with the strangest, loveliest eyes she had ever 
seen - big, yellow-brown eyes, almost golden.  

123
00:11:31,520 --> 00:11:37,440
Hares eyes, thought Jinny. The woman looked 
like a hare, with her long legs and thin face.

124
00:11:38,560 --> 00:11:41,120
'I can see that girl only thinks about clothes,'  

125
00:11:41,120 --> 00:11:44,080
said the Hare-woman to Jinny, 
and walked into the post office.  

126
00:11:45,200 --> 00:11:53,120
Jinny watched her go. What an interesting woman! 
she thought. And she understands about Rachel!

127
00:11:54,160 --> 00:11:57,280
Inside the post office the one 
o'clock news was on the radio.  

128
00:11:58,320 --> 00:12:01,520
The Hare-woman, Mrs Hollins, 
and Jinny all listened.
 
 

129
00:12:02,640 --> 00:12:05,680
Terrorists are holding 
thirteen-year-old Liam Shakespeare,  

130
00:12:05,680 --> 00:12:10,880
Harriet Shakespeare's son, at the family 
home in London. Police are trying to...
 
 

131
00:12:11,920 --> 00:12:16,800
'How terrible!' said Mrs Hollins. 'That poor boy!'

132
00:12:17,840 --> 00:12:21,040
'Who's Harriet Shakespeare?' asked Jinny.

133
00:12:22,080 --> 00:12:28,640
'You haven't heard of her?' asked the Hare-woman 
in surprise. 'She's a television reporter,  

134
00:12:28,640 --> 00:12:33,280
always looking for other people's 
secrets. Thinks herself very important.'

135
00:12:34,400 --> 00:12:39,760
Mrs Hollins pretended to feel sorry for 
Jinny. 'Poor girl, she doesn't have any  

136
00:12:39,760 --> 00:12:46,640
newspapers or radio or television in her house,' 
she explained. 'Her family grow their own food,  

137
00:12:46,640 --> 00:12:50,240
make their own clothes. They 
never buy anything new!'

138
00:12:51,360 --> 00:12:57,040
Mrs Hollins always laughs at us Slatterys, 
thought Jinny. 'We prefer to do everything  

139
00:12:57,040 --> 00:13:01,760
for ourselves,' she said. She really 
wanted the stranger to understand.

140
00:13:02,880 --> 00:13:08,480
But Mrs Hollins had started talking about the 
news again. 'That poor Harriet Shakespeare!  

141
00:13:09,520 --> 00:13:15,520
She must be very worried. A mother always 
worries about her children. Have you any  

142
00:13:15,520 --> 00:13:24,160
children?' she asked the Hare-woman. 'Ye-es, 
yes, I have. A son, Philip, almost fourteen.'

143
00:13:25,280 --> 00:13:32,400
'Well, well! My daughter Rachel and Jinny here are 
both nearly fourteen. Are you staying near here?'

144
00:13:33,360 --> 00:13:40,320
The Hare-woman laughed. 'Well, yes, we're staying 
in your cottage. We arrived late last night.'

145
00:13:41,360 --> 00:13:46,320
'Oh, you're Mrs Doyle!' Mrs Hollins 
said, and shook the stranger's hand  

146
00:13:46,320 --> 00:13:51,120
warmly. So the Hare-woman was one of the 
visitors to the cottage thought Jinny.

147
00:13:52,160 --> 00:13:56,560
'In fact, I hope we didn't wake 
everyone in the village up last night,'  

148
00:13:56,560 --> 00:14:02,080
said the Hare-woman. 'Philip fell 
over and crashed into some furniture.  

149
00:14:02,080 --> 00:14:07,040
There was a terrible noise. He hit his 
head, so he'll be in bed for a while.'

150
00:14:08,240 --> 00:14:10,800
Jinny said nothing, but she knew that wasn't true.

151
00:14:12,000 --> 00:14:16,240
'We were very tired,' continued the 
Hare-woman, 'so we took Philip upstairs  

152
00:14:16,240 --> 00:14:17,520
and went to bed immediately.'

153
00:14:18,560 --> 00:14:23,680
Another lie! thought Jinny. You 
didn't go to bed immediately.  

154
00:14:24,720 --> 00:14:27,760
You hammered and hammered. Why are you lying?

155
00:14:28,880 --> 00:14:31,280
Suddenly the Hare-woman 
seemed to remember something.  

156
00:14:32,400 --> 00:14:35,200
She stopped talking, bought 
some food and hurried out.

157
00:14:36,320 --> 00:14:41,280
Jinny walked slowly back to the farm. 
At first she had liked the stranger,  

158
00:14:41,280 --> 00:14:45,040
with her beautiful honest eyes. 
But why was she lying?
 
 
 
 

159
00:14:46,080 --> 00:14:46,800
CHAPTER TWO

160
00:14:48,000 --> 00:14:49,440
WHAT'S HAPPENING AT THE COTTAGE?

161
00:14:50,560 --> 00:14:53,440
DAY THREE - TUESDAY 9TH AUGUST

162
00:14:53,440 --> 00:14:54,480
8.00 A.M.

163
00:14:55,600 --> 00:15:01,360
Tug was lying on the bed. He hadn't slept since 
the Man and the Woman walked out after their  

164
00:15:01,360 --> 00:15:07,280
first visit, hours ago. The music had a strong 
beat which hammered at the inside of his head,  

165
00:15:07,280 --> 00:15:11,040
and it hadn't stopped all 
night. He was very tired,  

166
00:15:11,040 --> 00:15:15,520
and hungry and thirsty. But he was 
watching the door and waiting for Them.

167
00:15:16,560 --> 00:15:22,320
When the door opened, the music was louder for 
a moment as the Man entered. He looked at Tug.

168
00:15:23,360 --> 00:15:26,880
'Did you sleep well?' he asked, after a moment.

169
00:15:28,080 --> 00:15:30,880
'No,' said Tug. 'I - I'm thirsty.'

170
00:15:32,080 --> 00:15:37,520
'Have some water,' answered the Man. 'I've brought 
some.' And he offered Tug a glass of water.

171
00:15:38,480 --> 00:15:43,120
I'm not taking anything from you, Tug wanted 
to say, before you tell me what's happening.  

172
00:15:44,160 --> 00:15:48,560
But he was so thirsty! He took 
the glass and drank all the water.  

173
00:15:49,600 --> 00:15:51,840
Then he turned to the Man and said, 'Tell me-'

174
00:15:53,440 --> 00:15:55,360
'Sit down on the bed,' ordered the Man.

175
00:15:56,560 --> 00:16:00,400
Something in the Man's face told Tug 
that it was not a good idea to refuse.  

176
00:16:01,600 --> 00:16:07,840
He sat down. The Man opened the door and, while 
watching Tug carefully, put his arm outside.  

177
00:16:08,880 --> 00:16:10,400
And suddenly the music stopped.

178
00:16:11,440 --> 00:16:17,520
Tug fell back on the bed, free from the terrible 
noise at last. The room was beautifully silent.

179
00:16:18,640 --> 00:16:25,600
Then he heard someone climbing the stairs. 
The Woman walked in. She was carrying a tray.

180
00:16:26,640 --> 00:16:34,240
'Breakfast,' she said. 'Look.' It was a 
dream breakfast. A big plate of fried eggs,  

181
00:16:34,240 --> 00:16:37,280
tomatoes and bread, with a cup of hot, strong tea.

182
00:16:38,400 --> 00:16:45,040
Tug could not stop looking at the tray. But the 
Woman did not move. She stayed near the door.

183
00:16:46,160 --> 00:16:50,400
'Well?' he said at last. 'Isn't it for me?'

184
00:16:51,440 --> 00:16:56,960
'Oh yes,' she replied. 'It's for 
you. But what do you say first?'

185
00:16:58,080 --> 00:17:06,160
I'm not a child! thought Tug angrily. She's 
teaching me to be polite! But he was very hungry.

186
00:17:07,200 --> 00:17:08,160
'Thank you,' he said.

187
00:17:09,200 --> 00:17:11,680
'Thank you - what?' she asked.

188
00:17:12,720 --> 00:17:16,320
'I don't understand,' said Tug. Is this a game?

189
00:17:17,360 --> 00:17:19,520
'You usually call her something,' said the Man.

190
00:17:20,640 --> 00:17:24,240
Tug began to see what they 
wanted. Were they serious?  

191
00:17:25,360 --> 00:17:27,520
He pretended that he still didn't understand.

192
00:17:28,640 --> 00:17:31,840
'What do you mean? What do I usually call her?'

193
00:17:32,880 --> 00:17:39,360
It was the Woman who answered. 'You usually call 
me Ma. And your breakfast will be cold soon.'

194
00:17:40,400 --> 00:17:42,720
But Tug wasn't ready to do what they wanted yet.  

195
00:17:43,840 --> 00:17:46,400
He turned to the Man. 'And 
I suppose I call you Dad!'

196
00:17:47,440 --> 00:17:53,360
'No,' smiled the Man calmly. 'You could, 
but you don't. You call me Doyle.'

197
00:17:54,560 --> 00:18:03,040
Doyle... Ma... Tug looked from one to the other. 
It almost seemed true. Suddenly he shouted,  

198
00:18:03,040 --> 00:18:08,560
'You're crazy! All that's rubbish! Why 
don't you explain what's happening...'

199
00:18:09,680 --> 00:18:14,640
The door banged shut. The Woman had walked 
out and taken his breakfast with her.

200
00:18:15,680 --> 00:18:19,680
'That was stupid of you,' said 
Doyle. 'She's angry with you.  

201
00:18:20,800 --> 00:18:22,880
Mothers are like that sometimes, aren't they?'

202
00:18:23,840 --> 00:18:29,040
'But -' said Tug, and stopped. He could 
hear her climbing up the stairs again.

203
00:18:30,160 --> 00:18:32,720
'Now be careful this time,' said Doyle quietly.

204
00:18:33,840 --> 00:18:40,480
The Woman entered again, with the tray. Tug 
could smell the hot food. It looked wonderful.

205
00:18:41,680 --> 00:18:44,080
'Breakfast,' said the Woman, for the second time.

206
00:18:45,280 --> 00:18:52,240
What does it matter? thought Tug. Ma isn't 
what I call my mother. I call her Hank.

207
00:18:53,360 --> 00:19:00,320
'Thank you - Ma,' he said. The Woman gave him the 
tray, and left the room. As Doyle followed her,  

208
00:19:00,320 --> 00:19:04,720
he turned and smiled slowly at Tug. 
'Have a good breakfast - Philip.'

209
00:19:05,760 --> 00:19:13,280
'I'm not Philip!' Tug shouted. 'And you're not 
my parents!' But the door had already closed.

210
00:19:14,400 --> 00:19:18,960
And then the music started. With 
that terrible beat in his head,  

211
00:19:18,960 --> 00:19:20,880
he wasn't sure of anything any more.
 
 

212
00:19:21,840 --> 00:19:25,440
10.00 A.M.
Jinny was digging in the garden.  

213
00:19:26,560 --> 00:19:33,440
While she was working, she was talking angrily to 
herself. Forget it! Its nothing to do with you!  

214
00:19:34,480 --> 00:19:39,280
But she couldn't stop herself thinking of 
the Hare-woman. Why had she lied about the  

215
00:19:39,280 --> 00:19:43,760
noises in the night? And why had there 
been so much hammering at the cottage?

216
00:19:44,880 --> 00:19:48,880
Suddenly she had an idea. She 
could go up to the cottage now.  

217
00:19:50,000 --> 00:19:53,600
She knew that she should go on with her 
work - there were always lots of jobs to  

218
00:19:53,600 --> 00:19:57,920
do on the Slatterys' small farm - but she 
really wanted to understand the mystery.  

219
00:19:58,960 --> 00:20:03,760
Perhaps the Hare-woman had a good reason for lying 
and perhaps she would tell Jinny all about it...

220
00:20:04,960 --> 00:20:10,560
Soon she was walking up the narrow road to the 
moors. The cottage was on the left, but she didn't  

221
00:20:10,560 --> 00:20:16,400
go up to it. She climbed up the small hill behind 
the house, and hid in the trees halfway up the  

222
00:20:16,400 --> 00:20:22,080
hill. She couldn't see anybody in the cottage, 
but she could hear a radio playing loud music.

223
00:20:23,360 --> 00:20:27,840
Something was different about the 
cottage... Jinny went a few steps nearer,  

224
00:20:27,840 --> 00:20:30,000
to look more closely at the window in the roof...

225
00:20:31,200 --> 00:20:34,320
Suddenly a voice spoke from below. 'Hallo.'

226
00:20:35,440 --> 00:20:40,000
'Oh!' cried Jinny in surprise, and 
the branch that she was holding broke.  

227
00:20:41,200 --> 00:20:44,560
She fell, and slid all the way down 
the hill to the cottage garden.

228
00:20:45,680 --> 00:20:48,240
'Well, well!' said the voice.  

229
00:20:49,360 --> 00:20:55,840
Jinny looked up. It was a man with black 
hair and cold blue eyes. He looked angry.

230
00:20:56,880 --> 00:20:57,920
Jinny thought fast.  

231
00:20:59,040 --> 00:21:04,880
'I - I'm sorry, I didn't mean to - You see, I was 
looking for - for - mushrooms.' Would he believe  

232
00:21:04,880 --> 00:21:11,720
her? She continued quickly, 'They're very good 
to eat, er, fried in butter, for breakfast -'

233
00:21:13,280 --> 00:21:19,760
'Yes.' The cold voice stopped her. 'But perhaps 
you'd like to find a different place to look for  

234
00:21:19,760 --> 00:21:25,680
mushrooms. We're here on holiday, you see, and we 
don't want people crashing in through the kitchen  

235
00:21:25,680 --> 00:21:31,120
window.' He was holding her by the arm as he 
spoke, and pulling her away from the cottage.  

236
00:21:32,240 --> 00:21:33,200
Jinny was frightened.

237
00:21:34,400 --> 00:21:38,880
Just then she heard a single wild shout from 
inside the cottage, followed immediately  

238
00:21:38,880 --> 00:21:45,680
by a crashing sound. The loud music went on 
playing. The man shouted towards the house,  

239
00:21:45,680 --> 00:21:51,040
'Oh, be quiet, Philip!' He's pretending 
to be a father who's angry with his son,  

240
00:21:51,040 --> 00:21:57,840
thought Jinny, but I don't believe him! Why is he 
so cold and unfriendly? Is he hiding something?

241
00:21:59,040 --> 00:22:02,960
But she was shaking a little after her 
fall, and she was still afraid of the man.  

242
00:22:04,080 --> 00:22:07,760
So she pulled her arm away, and 
said quickly, 'I - I must go home.'  

243
00:22:08,880 --> 00:22:11,840
She knew that he was watching her as 
she hurried away from the cottage.
 
 

244
00:22:13,040 --> 00:22:17,040
10.30 A.M.
The music was still playing in the bedroom.  

245
00:22:18,240 --> 00:22:22,320
Tug had just finished his breakfast when 
he heard the noise of Jinny's fall outside.  

246
00:22:23,440 --> 00:22:29,120
He jumped on to the bed and looked out of the 
window. He could only see the sky and the tops of  

247
00:22:29,120 --> 00:22:34,480
trees, but he heard a girl saying, 'They're very 
good to eat, fried in butter, for breakfast -' Who  

248
00:22:34,480 --> 00:22:41,840
was she? Could he send her a message? Would it 
be dangerous? Then he heard feet running up the  

249
00:22:41,840 --> 00:22:49,040
stairs. It was now or never. He pushed open the 
window and shouted as loudly as possible, 'Help!'

250
00:22:50,160 --> 00:22:53,600
The next moment the Woman had crashed into him.  

251
00:22:53,600 --> 00:22:57,920
He fell on to the floor, and she held him 
down with one strong hand over his mouth.  

252
00:22:59,040 --> 00:23:02,400
She only let him get up when she heard 
the Man come back into the house.

253
00:23:03,600 --> 00:23:11,280
'Right!' she said. 'Now you learn to obey 
orders!' She hit him hard across the face,  

254
00:23:11,280 --> 00:23:16,480
on one side and then the other. She went 
on hitting him, in time to the beat of  

255
00:23:16,480 --> 00:23:23,440
the music. Tug began to think that she would 
never stop. He was trying hard not to scream,  

256
00:23:23,440 --> 00:23:30,320
because when he started, he would go on and on, 
like her... Then suddenly Doyle was there. He put  

257
00:23:30,320 --> 00:23:40,000
a finger on the Woman's arm. Just one finger. 
And no words. But it was enough. She stopped.

258
00:23:41,120 --> 00:23:49,840
'Stupid woman,' said Doyle calmly. 'Stupid to hit 
his face. Get some water.' She went downstairs.

259
00:23:50,720 --> 00:23:54,840
'She hit me,' said Tug. 'Just because I -'

260
00:23:55,440 --> 00:24:00,240
'You have to understand,' Doyle said 
quietly. 'We'll kill you if we have to.'

261
00:24:01,440 --> 00:24:07,120
The room seemed very quiet, although the music 
was still playing. I've never been really afraid  

262
00:24:07,120 --> 00:24:14,800
before, thought Tug. He was full of a deep, cold 
fear. For the first time in his life, he realized  

263
00:24:14,800 --> 00:24:22,080
that he could die. Not in a hundred years, or 
when he was very old, but now. Today or tomorrow.

264
00:24:23,120 --> 00:24:29,040
But the moment passed. Soon Doyle and the Woman 
were washing Tug's face, like careful parents.  

265
00:24:30,160 --> 00:24:32,800
When the Woman left the 
room, Doyle sat by the door.  

266
00:24:34,000 --> 00:24:40,080
Now he had a gun with him, which he was cleaning. 
Tug could not take his eyes off the cold grey gun.  

267
00:24:41,120 --> 00:24:44,080
Perhaps he's going to kill me 
now... to shoot me with the gun...

268
00:24:45,200 --> 00:24:51,200
At last Doyle put the gun down. Suddenly 
angry, Tug shouted, 'How can you two pretend  

269
00:24:51,200 --> 00:24:57,280
to be my parents? Look what that woman 
did to my face! She can't be my mother!'

270
00:24:58,240 --> 00:25:03,840
'Most murders happen in the family, you know. Your 
family are the people who can give you most pain.  

271
00:25:04,960 --> 00:25:08,160
They know how to hurt you. Parents are the worst.'

272
00:25:09,280 --> 00:25:12,480
'Then why are you trying to hurt me?' asked Tug.

273
00:25:13,520 --> 00:25:17,520
'Trying to hurt you? No, Philip, 
we're doing our best for you.  

274
00:25:18,640 --> 00:25:23,040
But we're prisoners of the family 
ourselves. Like the rest of the world.'

275
00:25:24,160 --> 00:25:26,240
And he smiled as he picked up his gun again.
 
 

276
00:25:27,440 --> 00:25:30,640
11.00 A.M.
Jinny was still  

277
00:25:30,640 --> 00:25:35,520
running when she reached the village. I must 
tell Keith what's happening at the cottage!  

278
00:25:36,480 --> 00:25:40,720
I know he'll listen to me! Keith 
was Rachel Hollins' brother,  

279
00:25:40,720 --> 00:25:44,800
and Jinny's best friend in the village, 
although he was five years older than her.

280
00:25:45,760 --> 00:25:50,240
She found him in the Hollins' sitting-room, with 
a lot of different newspapers in front of him.

281
00:25:51,280 --> 00:26:02,280
'Keith!' she cried. 'I've got to tell you! It was 
so awful! I didn't do anything wrong but he -'

282
00:26:02,800 --> 00:26:04,960
She began to cry as she started speaking.  

283
00:26:06,000 --> 00:26:09,840
But Keith always took care of 
her. He gave her his cup of tea.

284
00:26:11,280 --> 00:26:13,440
'Now, drink that, Jinny,' he told her.  

285
00:26:14,400 --> 00:26:18,240
'You'll feel better in a moment. 
Then tell me all about it.'

286
00:26:19,360 --> 00:26:23,840
She told him about the people at the cottage, 
and explained how the Hare-woman had told lies  

287
00:26:23,840 --> 00:26:28,640
in Mrs Hollins' shop. 'So I went to 
the cottage to see,' she continued.  

288
00:26:29,680 --> 00:26:33,280
'And I slid down the hill behind the 
house - and there was an awful man  

289
00:26:33,280 --> 00:26:37,840
who told me to go away. But the really 
important thing is what I heard!'

290
00:26:38,640 --> 00:26:44,000
'Tell me quickly, or I'll die of excitement.' 
Keith was laughing quietly to himself.

291
00:26:45,200 --> 00:26:52,320
'Listen,' she said angrily. 'It's serious. 
I heard someone shouting "Help!" And the  

292
00:26:52,320 --> 00:26:56,160
person who shouted meant it. 
Now what do you think, Keith?'

293
00:26:57,360 --> 00:27:02,880
'Well,' said Keith, after thinking for a moment. 
'Perhaps someone was just playing a game.'

294
00:27:03,920 --> 00:27:11,680
'A game! No! There was hammering - and she told 
lies - and I heard the shout! These are facts!'

295
00:27:12,800 --> 00:27:18,480
'These newspapers have all got facts in,' said 
Keith. 'But they make different stories out of  

296
00:27:18,480 --> 00:27:24,160
the same facts. That's my school work for the 
summer - to take a story and follow it in all  

297
00:27:24,160 --> 00:27:29,040
the newspapers for a week, to see how different 
the stories are, although the facts are the same.  

298
00:27:30,080 --> 00:27:32,000
Can you think of a story that I could follow?'

299
00:27:33,040 --> 00:27:38,400
Jinny remembered the Hare-woman in the shop, 
listening to the radio. 'You could do the story  

300
00:27:38,400 --> 00:27:44,720
of Harriet Shakespeare's son, you know, held by 
terrorists. But Keith, you're forgetting my story!  

301
00:27:45,840 --> 00:27:49,360
What about the voice that 
shouted "Help!"? What can I do?'

302
00:27:50,480 --> 00:27:55,120
'I agree it is a bit strange. But 
there's probably a good reason for it.  

303
00:27:56,160 --> 00:27:59,840
If you find some more facts, I'll 
ask my father to investigate it.  

304
00:28:00,880 --> 00:28:05,760
But now I really must start reading 
these newspapers. Sorry I can't help.'

305
00:28:06,800 --> 00:28:10,320
I'll investigate it myself, 
thought Jinny crossly.
 
 

306
00:28:11,360 --> 00:28:15,840
DAY FOUR - WEDNESDAY 10TH AUGUST
11.00 A.M.

307
00:28:16,640 --> 00:28:22,960
Tug felt terrible. The music had given 
him a headache. He was alone for a moment,  

308
00:28:22,960 --> 00:28:28,800
while Doyle and the Woman were downstairs. He 
looked tiredly round the room, at the cupboard,  

309
00:28:28,800 --> 00:28:35,360
the walls, the wallpaper ... An idea suddenly 
came to him. I'll tear a piece of paper off  

310
00:28:35,360 --> 00:28:40,560
the wall behind the cupboard, nobody will 
notice... He pulled at a corner of the paper.  

311
00:28:41,600 --> 00:28:48,480
Hurry, hurry! One of Them will be back soon. 
Now he had a large piece of paper in his hand.  

312
00:28:49,600 --> 00:28:54,240
With the pencil that he always kept in his 
pocket, he wrote a few words quickly on the paper.  

313
00:28:55,440 --> 00:28:59,280
Then, with his hands shaking, he folded 
the paper into the shape of a dart.  

314
00:29:00,400 --> 00:29:06,720
Hurry, hurry! He jumped on to the bed, pushed his 
arm through the bars, and threw the dart as far  

315
00:29:06,720 --> 00:29:12,800
as possible out of the open window. That's your 
only chance to get a message to the outside world,  

316
00:29:12,800 --> 00:29:16,480
he told himself. I hope that 
someone finds it soon!
 
 
 
 

317
00:29:17,600 --> 00:29:18,400
CHAPTER THREE

318
00:29:19,520 --> 00:29:20,240
FREE PEOPLE

319
00:29:21,280 --> 00:29:24,800
DAY FIVE - THURSDAY 11TH AUGUST

320
00:29:24,800 --> 00:29:25,840
6.30 A.M.

321
00:29:26,640 --> 00:29:31,680
As Jinny did her work on the farm, she could not 
stop thinking about the mystery of the Hare-woman  

322
00:29:31,680 --> 00:29:38,560
and her son. She was hoping to go back to the 
cottage today. But at breakfast her father said,  

323
00:29:38,560 --> 00:29:42,560
'You'll have to make the butter today, Jinny, 
because your mother is making the bread.  

324
00:29:43,600 --> 00:29:47,360
Oz,' he said to Jinny's young brother, 
'you're coming to help me mend the walls  

325
00:29:47,360 --> 00:29:52,080
round the south field. And Jinny, you'll 
have to plant the vegetables as well.  

326
00:29:53,120 --> 00:29:57,840
I think you'll have time. There's a 
lot to do before harvest next week.'

327
00:29:58,960 --> 00:30:08,000
Thanks a lot! Jinny thought angrily. Don't I 
get any time for myself? It's always the same!

328
00:30:08,000 --> 00:30:10,800
Later she talked to her mother, Bella, about it.

329
00:30:12,000 --> 00:30:17,360
'Mum, why do I have to spend all my time 
working on the farm? It's the summer holidays  

330
00:30:17,360 --> 00:30:23,840
now. My school friends all get up late 
and go riding. Or shopping, like Rachel.'

331
00:30:25,040 --> 00:30:28,480
'Jinny, you know why we decided 
to leave London and buy this farm.  

332
00:30:29,600 --> 00:30:36,560
Joe was working much too hard in London. His 
work was making him ill. We wanted a healthier,  

333
00:30:36,560 --> 00:30:41,040
freer life. I agree that it's hard 
work, but we chose this life.'

334
00:30:42,080 --> 00:30:45,680
'You two chose it, you mean. No one asked me.'

335
00:30:46,720 --> 00:30:50,320
'All children get the life 
that their parents have chosen.  

336
00:30:50,320 --> 00:30:52,480
You can choose your own life 
when you're old enough.'

337
00:30:53,520 --> 00:30:57,440
'But I want some time now! 
I'm - I'm so angry with Dad!  

338
00:30:58,480 --> 00:31:04,320
He gives me too much work to do. 
Sometimes I - I almost want to kill him!'

339
00:31:04,320 --> 00:31:09,920
Her mother did not reply immediately. Then she 
said quietly, 'It's because you love him that  

340
00:31:09,920 --> 00:31:16,640
you want to kill him. But it's the wrong answer. 
If you kill the people who you love, or run away  

341
00:31:16,640 --> 00:31:22,560
from them, you only destroy yourself in the end. 
You have to accept them, or change yourself.'

342
00:31:23,760 --> 00:31:28,800
Suddenly Jinny realized that it was 
true. Accepting what other people wanted,  

343
00:31:28,800 --> 00:31:33,040
and working together - that was family 
life. She smiled at her mother.
 
 

344
00:31:34,480 --> 00:31:37,600
5.30 P.M.
Doyle looked at his watch.  

345
00:31:38,800 --> 00:31:40,080
'Time to go downstairs.'

346
00:31:41,280 --> 00:31:49,280
'What?' said Tug. He had been there for almost 
five days now. Was it possible to leave the room?

347
00:31:50,320 --> 00:31:55,440
Doyle pushed him towards the door, and they 
went down the stairs. At the same moment  

348
00:31:55,440 --> 00:32:00,480
Doyle turned off the music. For the last 
two days it had not stopped for a second.  

349
00:32:01,680 --> 00:32:04,880
Now, the house was suddenly 
silent, and Tug felt frightened.

350
00:32:06,000 --> 00:32:11,760
They were in a big sitting-room, full of old heavy 
furniture. The Woman was sitting in an armchair.

351
00:32:12,880 --> 00:32:19,120
'Sit down,' she said to Tug. 'We're going to have 
a nice family evening in front of the television.'

352
00:32:20,240 --> 00:32:25,840
Clearly, Tug's visit downstairs was planned. 
The television news was just starting.

353
00:32:26,800 --> 00:32:31,120
Of course! thought Tug. I'll be in the news!

354
00:32:32,240 --> 00:32:36,640
'Good evening. The terrorists who 
are holding thirteen-year-old Liam  

355
00:32:36,640 --> 00:32:40,320
Shakespeare at his home in London have 
said that they belong to "Free People".  

356
00:32:41,280 --> 00:32:44,560
That is the revolutionary group 
which wants to end family life.  

357
00:32:45,680 --> 00:32:49,760
They say that they want all children and adults 
to live free from the prison of the family.'

358
00:32:50,800 --> 00:32:57,680
What's happening? thought Tug. Am I 
crazy? How can I be here and in London?

359
00:32:58,800 --> 00:33:03,200
'Our reporter spoke to Liam's mother, Harriet 
Shakespeare, at a friend's house today.'

360
00:33:04,160 --> 00:33:09,840
There was Hank. Her small face looked tired, and 
Tug could see that she was trying not to cry.  

361
00:33:11,200 --> 00:33:13,760
Hank, Hank, come and save me from these people!

362
00:33:14,800 --> 00:33:19,280
'Mrs Shakespeare, have you spoken 
to your son?' asked the reporter.

363
00:33:20,320 --> 00:33:26,400
'No,' replied Hank. 'But we can see him moving 
around in the house, so we know he's still alive.'

364
00:33:27,520 --> 00:33:29,600
'Why do you think this group has taken your son?'

365
00:33:30,720 --> 00:33:34,320
'Well, I suppose that it's because I've 
investigated Free People in the past.  

366
00:33:35,360 --> 00:33:38,160
It's my job to investigate revolutionary groups.'

367
00:33:39,280 --> 00:33:42,720
'You have always said that nobody should 
give terrorist groups what they want.  

368
00:33:43,760 --> 00:33:46,640
Do you still think that, now 
that your own son is in danger?'

369
00:33:47,760 --> 00:33:54,160
'Yes, I do. But we - we don't know yet what 
the group wants. We'll have to wait and see.'

370
00:33:55,280 --> 00:34:02,480
That's a lie! Tug thought. He always knew 
when Hank was lying. But she seemed to  

371
00:34:02,480 --> 00:34:07,520
believe that he was held by terrorists in 
London. And the reporters believed it too.

372
00:34:08,640 --> 00:34:10,800
Doyle and the Woman were watching him carefully.

373
00:34:11,840 --> 00:34:16,720
'It's interesting to hear about your 
friend Liam, isn't it?' Doyle said slowly.

374
00:34:17,760 --> 00:34:24,320
'He isn't my friend-' began Tug. Then 
he stopped. He remembered Hank saying,  

375
00:34:24,320 --> 00:34:31,840
We can see him moving around. Suddenly he 
felt very tired. Who am I? Where's home?  

376
00:34:32,880 --> 00:34:37,280
In the bedroom, with the music, 
he would feel better. He stood up.

377
00:34:38,240 --> 00:34:39,760
'I want to go back upstairs.'

378
00:34:40,960 --> 00:34:44,800
Doyle put an arm round Tug, and led 
him upstairs like a small child.
 
 

379
00:34:45,920 --> 00:34:47,840
8.00 P.M. 

380
00:34:49,120 --> 00:34:52,000
Keith was very excited about 
the Liam Shakespeare story.

381
00:34:53,040 --> 00:34:56,400
'Don't you think it's strange?' he asked Jinny.

382
00:34:57,440 --> 00:35:03,760
'What do you mean?' she answered. She was 
very tired after a long day on the farm.

383
00:35:04,880 --> 00:35:10,640
'Well, I've just shown you all the newspapers 
and the video of the six o'clock news. There's  

384
00:35:10,640 --> 00:35:16,720
Harriet Shakespeare, a brave, loving mother, 
worried about her son. A picture of mother-love  

385
00:35:16,720 --> 00:35:23,680
and happy families. But it's the wrong picture, 
isn't it? The terrorists have made a bad mistake.'

386
00:35:24,800 --> 00:35:26,800
Jinny was too tired to think clearly.  

387
00:35:27,840 --> 00:35:32,000
'What do they care? They just want 
money or something, don't they?'

388
00:35:33,120 --> 00:35:38,480
